<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900924-0130</DOCNO><DOCID>900924-0130.</DOCID><HL>   Commodities:   CFTC Rules Crude   Sold as 15-Day Brent   Isn't Futures Contract</HL><DATE>09/24/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2</SO><IN>PETROLEUM (PET)COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)</IN><GV>COMMODITY FUTURES TRADING COMMISSION (CFT)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Commodity Futures Trading Commission, asexpected, approved a &quot;statutory interpretation&quot; that crudeoil sold under so-called 15-day Brent oil contracts isn't afutures contract as defined in the Commodity Exchange Act.   The commission, by a 3-1 vote, declared that the contractsdescribe cash sales of commodities for deferred shipment ordelivery. As such, these contracts are excluded from theCFTC's regulatory jurisdiction.</LP><TEXT>   The issue arose in April, when U.S. District Court JudgeWilliam Connor in New York ruled in a case brought byTransnor (Bermuda) Ltd. that forward trading in Brent, awidely traded North Sea crude, should be regulated in thesame way as a U.S. futures contract.   Judge Connor's opinion initially placed a cloud over theentire crude oil market. Non-U.S. participants fearedentering into Brent contracts that might subsequently be heldunenforceable. U.S. participants shied away from the market,believing they could be held in violation of the CommodityExchange Act.   CFTC Chairman Wendy Gramm and Commissioners Kalo Hinemanand William Albrecht voted to approve the statutoryinterpretation, and Commissioner Fowler West dissented.</TEXT></DOC>